#### Express Routers

A router is like a mini application, it contains its own set of middlewares and routes. We use router to break down our application and make it more modular.

We can create route using express object `const friendsRouter = express.Router();`

We mount a router as we use middleware: `app.use(friendsRouter)`

Special thing that routers allow us to do is that we can mount group of routes under a specific path: `app.use("/friends",friendsRouter);` . So, our get request becomes: `app.get("/", friendsController.getFriends);`

Example `routes>friends.router.js`: 

```plaintext
const express = require('express');

const friendsController = require("../controllers/friends.controller");

const friendsRouter = express.Router();

friendsRouter.get("/", friendsController.getFriends);
friendsRouter.get(":friendId", friendsController.getFriendById);
friendsRouter.post("/friends", friendsController.postFriends);

module.exports = friendsRouter;
```

To use this router in the server, we have to add following code in `server.js`:

```plaintext
const friendsRouter = require("./routes/friends.router");
app.use("/friends", friendsRouter);
```

_Using this method, we can also add specific middleware to specific router._

### _Best Practices when building RESTFUL APIs_

_A RESTful API is an API that follows **RE**presentational **S**tate **T**ransfer model._ It is a set of guidelines and best practices that are derived from Roy Fielding's original paper.

The Representation and State, both refer to how server makes your data available, and the transfer part talks about how it is sent to the user.

It says, endpoints are collections of data that are stored on the server side.

We use GET, POST, PUT, and DELETE to perform action on the collection of data.

It involves client and server architecture, where Client displays our data to the server and allows them to perform actions which are sent to the server which perform actions, both have different jobs and communicate with each other to get the job done.

Our requests are both stateless and cacheable, i.e. each request is separate and not connected to the state of the client. We don't store data in a session variable like PHP does. Our request keep track of all our state, which means we can cache requests by saving the result for future use.

*   Use plurals while requesting, adding or deleting collections.

### CRUD (Create, Read, Update and Delete)

POST → Create

GET → Read

PUT → Update/ Replace: Replacing entire collection element by new one

PATCH → Update / Modify: Replacing certain property

DELETE → Delete

### Sending Files as response

To send a file we can make use of `sendFile()` method of response object, but we also need path of the file resource. So for this we make use of `path` library as path handling vary from OS to OS.

```plaintext
const path = require('path');

function getMessages(req, res){
    const pathToFile = path.join(__dirname, '..','public', 'mountains.png');
    res.sendFile(pathToFile);
}
```

_\_\_dirname:_ It refers to the path of current directory in which the file containing this property is placed.

### Sending websites with Node

`app.use("/site",express.static(path.join(__dirname, "public")));`

This code makes public folder available to server making it available to request.

_Only host files in small size applications, if files are many use CDN services like Amazon Alkemai._

### Using Templating Engine

Express supports several templating engine like EJS, Handlebars (hbs).

A templating engine replaces marked expressions with values which come from the server, and tranforms the document into a HTML file.

After installing a templating engine library, we just need to tell it where are the templates present.

General Syntax to use template engine:

`app.set('view engine', <Name of templating engine>);`

To set up parameters for it:

`app.set(<property name>, <property value>);`

To return the reponse as a template page we use `.render(<filename (without extension)>, <object with keys as variable name and values as variable values>);`

### Logging requests with morgan

It can log requests that our server is being logged for

`npm install morgan`

Now add it into middleware chain after security related middleware.

`app.use(morgan("combined"));`

Now in terminal you can see the log for every request made to your REST API.
